<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0147-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Document Signed: a document not in the authors handwriting, but signed by the author  ]">DS</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>; 
copy, David Humphreys biographical sketch of GW, c.August 1786, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Rosenbach Museum and Library, Philadelphia, Pa. ]">PPRF</span>.
 For a description of Humphreys sketch, see <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ W. W. Abbot et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;The Papers of George Washington, Colonial Series&lt;/i&gt;. 10 vols. Charlottesville, Va., 198395. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Papers, Colonial Series</span></span>, 1:173.</p>


   <p>The address is in Robert Stewarts hand, and its style suggests that it was of his composition.</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0147-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0147-fn-0001">1</a>
   
   <p>Stewart and the officers at Fort Loudoun did not know of GWs actual resignation until 13 Jan., when Stewart received a letter from GW which probably enclosed <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-06-02-0152" class="document">GWs reply of 10 Jan. 1759</a> to this address of 31 Dec. 1758 from the officers of his regiment.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0147-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0147-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>The two columns of names appear in the manuscript as they do here, but it was certainly intended by this arrangement that Stewarts name head the list followed by the other captains, McNeill, Woodward, McKenzie, and Bullitt. Among the names of the senior officers of the regiment missing are those of Lt. Col. Adam Stephen who left Fort Loudoun on 29 Dec. (see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-06-02-0145" class="document">Stewart to GW, that date</a>), Maj. Andrew Lewis who was a prisoner of the French, Capt. Thomas Waggener who was in Pittsburgh, Capt. Walter Steuart who, after being wounded in September, had gone to New York, and Ens. Thomas Gist, who was also wounded and held prisoner by the Indians. All of the officers have been identified in this or earlier volumes of the <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ W. W. Abbot et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;The Papers of George Washington, Colonial Series&lt;/i&gt;. 10 vols. Charlottesville, Va., 198395. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Papers, Colonial Series</span></span>.</p>

</div>
